{
  "doc_id": "20531",
  "text": "The most widely used approach to direct small molecules to mitochondria in vivo is by conjugation to a lipophilic cation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ( Figure 1A ). The charge is spread over a large, hydrophobic surface area, allowing these cations to pass easily through membranes and accumulate in the mitochondrial matrix in response to the membrane potential [CITATION_3] . The Nernst equation indicates that the uptake of singly charged cations increases 10-fold for every 61.5 mV of membrane potential at 37°C [CITATION_4] ; therefore, lipophilic cations should concentrate several hundred-fold greater in mitochondria ( Figure 1A ). The lipophilic triphenylphosphonium cation (TPP) has been the most widely used to direct a range of moieties to mitochondria in vivo, including redox probes, antioxidants and spin traps [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . The TPP moiety is relatively easy to introduce into a compound by displacing a leaving group by reaction with triphenylphosphine [CITATION_8] . TPP cations are accumulated by mitochondria within organs such as the heart, liver and kidneys in vivo following oral, intravenous or intraperitoneal delivery consistent with their uptake from the circulation driven by the plasma and mitochondrial membrane potentials [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Therefore, the TPP moiety has been widely used to target many molecules to mitochondria, both as probes and as potential therapies. In the following section, I consider the development of mitochondria-targeted antioxidants.",
